/**
 * @brief Checks if a subarray can be sorted by cyclic shifts.
 * 
 * A subarray can be sorted by cyclic shifts if and only if it is a permutation
 * of a sorted sequence. This means the set of elements in the subarray must be
 * the same as the set of elements in the sorted version of the subarray.
 * Since cyclic shifts only reorder elements within the subarray, the set of 
 * elements must remain invariant.
 * 
 * More strongly, if we can sort the subarray using only cyclic shifts, 
 * it means the elements must already be "cyclically sorted" relative to their target positions.
 *
 * For a subarray S of length k, let S_sorted be the sorted version of S.
 * S can be transformed into S_sorted via cyclic shifts if and only if S_sorted is a cyclic shift of S.
 * 
 * A simpler necessary and sufficient condition for a sequence A of length k to be sortable 
 * via cyclic shifts to its sorted version S_sorted is that the elements of A must be 
 * the same as the elements of S_sorted (which is always true if we only shift).
 * The actual condition is that the elements of A must be in a specific cyclic order.
 * 
 * If we sort the subarray to get S_sorted, S must be a cyclic shift of S_sorted.
 * E.g., if S_sorted = [1, 2, 3], then S could be [1, 2, 3], [2, 3, 1], or [3, 1, 2].
 * 
 * @param sub The subarray.
 * @return true if it can be sorted by cyclic shifts, false otherwise.
 */
bool can_sort_by_cyclic_shift(std::vector<long long> sub) {
    int k = sub.size();
    if (k == 0) return true;

    std::vector<long long> sorted_sub = sub;
    std::sort(sorted_sub.begin(), sorted_sub.end());

    // Check if 'sub' is a cyclic shift of 'sorted_sub'
    // We concatenate sorted_sub with itself and check if sub is a substring of the result.
    std::vector<long long> doubled_sorted_sub = sorted_sub;
    doubled_sorted_sub.insert(doubled_sorted_sub.end(), sorted_sub.begin(), sorted_sub.end());

